The start symbol is  

S → NT14 NT72  

Therefore the string must be the concatenation of a substring produced by NT14 followed immediately by a substring produced by NT72.

The only grammar rule that yields the terminal token t 82 is  

NT72 → 't82'

No other non‑terminal has a production for t 82.  
Consequently, every occurrence of t 82 in any derivation must be the entire yield of a single NT72, i.e. it has to be the very last token of the whole string.

In the string we are asked to parse, t 82 appears as the 14‑th token, followed by eighteen additional tokens:

… t86  t82  t36  t79  …  t14  t59

Since t 82 is not the final token, NT72 cannot generate this suffix, and hence S cannot generate the whole string.

Therefore the given grammar does not generate the supplied string.

No

The start symbol S expands in exactly one way:

S → NT14  NT72

So the string must be split into two contiguous parts,  
the left part deriving NT14 and the right part deriving NT72.

1.  Location of NT72  
    NT72 can be obtained only by  
        – the single–terminal productions NT72 → 't82' | 't54' | 't60' | 't62', or  
        – the two binary productions NT72 → NT70 NT59 and NT72 → NT75 NT3.  

    In the given string the only symbol that could match one of the four single‑
    terminal possibilities is the fourth token ‘t60’.  But ‘t60’ is not the final
    token of the string, so NT72 cannot be the rightmost non‑terminal if it is
    produced by a single‑terminal rule.  Therefore NT72 would have to be produced
    by one of its two binary rules.

2.  Consequences of the binary alternatives  
    • NT72 → NT70 NT59  
      None of the seven tokens (2…8) is a terminal of NT70 (t57, t7, t53, t25, t73, t18, t70)
      or of NT59 (t56, t74, t81).  Hence, for NT70 and NT59 to be derived they would
      each have to cover at least two tokens.  Whatever split point is chosen,
      the left block would have to derive NT70 and the right block NT59, yet the
      required terminals for these symbols never appear in the appropriate order.
      Checking all possible 1…6 / 6…1 splits shows no pair (NT70, NT59) is
      obtainable.

    • NT72 → NT75 NT3  
      The only terminals of NT75 are t69, t29, t31, t88 and of NT3 are t55, t91.
      None of those terminals occurs in positions 2…8, so both NT75 and NT3 would
      again have to span at least two tokens each.  A systematic inspection of
      all binary rules that could eventually generate NT75 or NT3 from the
      available single‑token non‑terminals proves impossible: every required
      intermediate symbol ultimately demands one of the missing terminals
      (t69, t29, t31, t88, t55, t91).  Thus the pair (NT75, NT3) cannot be realised
      either.

3.  Conclusion for NT72  
   Because neither of the two binary possibilities works and the single‑terminal
   possibilities are impossible at the end of the string, the right‑hand symbol
   NT72 cannot generate any suffix of the given string.

4.  Since NT72 cannot cover any suffix, S cannot derive the whole string.

Therefore the grammar does not generate the string.

No
